A new doctrine I think fits the Money Bin

Micro-Correction Principle

Large successes rarely require one giant correction.

They usually emerge from many small, calibrated corrections.

Loop:

Measure
↓
Estimate
↓
Correct 2%
↓
Observe
↓
Re-range
↓
Repeat

The key idea is that you don’t need a perfect world model. You need a model that’s accurate enough to choose the next useful adjustment and then improve it with feedback. Over time, those incremental corrections compound into large changes in trajectory. That’s a pattern that transfers across many domains because it’s fundamentally about adaptive decision-making under uncertainty, not about any one specific field.